name: RAMZY HAMAD
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport at age 10 in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Reason', 'He discovered his love for equestrian after first jumping with one of his father\'s Arabian horses. "My father bought us eight horses to keep on the farm. My brothers and I started riding, especially my eldest brother who had a bit more experience with horses." (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012; horsetimesegypt.com, 22 Aug 2011)'), ('Debut', '1990 for Saudi Arabia, in Yokohama, Japan (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTIn 2012 he was a member of the team that won Saudi Arabia\'s first team medal in equestrian at the Olympic Games when they claimed bronze in jumping in London. (ashgabat2017.com, 20 Sep 2017; saudiequestrian.com, 19 Oct 2013)BUSINESSMANHe has been a partner in one of Saudi Arabia\'s leading contracting companies. He has also run an equestrian business called Elite Horses in Saudi Arabia that offers training for horses and riders, tack and feed shops, an equine transportation company and a stable construction and management business. "I want to be able to provide the Arab region with the same quality of equestrian services that other countries offer today. After all, we come from a part of the world where horses are a part of our identity and are revered as symbols of freedom, strength and power." (cavalor.com, 20 Mar 2015; elitehorses.com, 2011)OTHER ACTIVITIESHe has served as president of the International Equestrian Federation [FEI] Arab Riders club committee. He has also worked as trainer of the Saudi young riders jumping team. (elitehorses.com, 2011) '), ('Hero', 'His mother. (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Influence', 'His father. (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Relatives', 'His brother Sami Al Duhami has worked as an equestrian coach. (saudiaramcoworld.com, 31 Jan 2011)'), ('Injuries', 'He broke his back at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney after his horse slipped. It took him five months to recover. name: KHALED ABDULAZIZ
bio: [('Beginning', 'He first tried the sport at age 10. His father was a breeder of Arabian horses in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, and taught Al Eid and his four younger brothers to ride. name: FARAH
bio: [('Beginning', 'She was first introduced to the sport briefly in 2012, but did not start regular training until 2014. (fairobserver.com, 06 Nov 2015; arabnews.com, 18 Nov 2015)'), ('Reason', '"I\'ve always been involved in sports. I did taekwondo, swimming, gymnastics. I was first introduced to ju-jitsu through a friend. I was learning taekwondo at the time, and I was told that ju-jitsu is the most superior form of martial arts. I wasn\'t very interested at first, but ju-jitsu kept finding its way back into my life. I took up a KickFit class, and my instructor encouraged me to give ju-jitsu a chance. I could also see the ju-jitsu class in training from across the dojo, and I was struck by the grace of their movements. I think getting to watch them train day in and day out was what finally convinced me that this is something I should try." (arabnews.com, 18 Nov 2015)'), ('Ambition', 'To become world champion. (fairobserver.com, 05 Nov 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralADVANCING WOMEN\'S SPORTShe hopes to one day open a fighting gym in Saudi Arabia for female competitors. "I want to open up a school in Saudi Arabia for girls to train in martial arts. I\'m kind of working on that. I think more Saudi girls should be involved in sports because they should be able to be healthier, not only their bodies, but their minds should be healthier - they should be able to stand up for themselves. Sports should be in every school in Saudi. Not sports as in training and competing, but just going to the gym and having a workout or keeping healthier, it affects a lot of things. Not only your body, but your mind as well. It plays a big, big role in people\'s lives in general." (fairobserver.com, 05 Nov 2015)TRAINING IN JORDANShe lives and trains in Jordan, where she feels that women in sport are more accepted. She says she has received negative criticism in her home country for competing in her sport. "In Jordan, people are more open-minded than in the Gulf. We have female boxers, and football players and basketball players, so sports are something common here. In general they\'re more open-minded than people in Saudi Arabia. My relatives in Saudi, they are supportive, but they don\'t know exactly what I\'m doing and they don\'t really ask. Some of the Saudi people are very negative. I [received] very negative criticism when my pictures were online on social media because I was the first Saudi to ever compete in BJJ and people said I was a sinner. Like, \'She\'s going to hell\'. I was questioning myself. I thought maybe I\'m doing something wrong, like I wasn\'t raised \'right\'. But there\'s nothing wrong with what I do." (fairobserver.com, 05 Nov 2015; Facebook profile, 23 Jun 2018) '), ('Influence', 'Her father. (arabnews.com, 18 Nov 2015)'), ('Education', 'International Relations, Political Science - University of Jordan, Jordan'), ('Languages', 'Arabic, English'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Championships7Newaza -55kg2016Ashgabat, TKM')]
